Drunk with corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he not drive.
He asked me why.
« You have drunk, » I said to him, « aren't you afraid of the police? »
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Obviously, I knew that the police take bribes, but I worried that Boris might encounter a policeman who was not corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to get into the police department responsible for traffic, you have to buy your chief's silence.
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things the right way drown in bureaucratic hassles.
By paying $100, you can drive around town without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those who aren't offered any, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a disaster or an abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officials and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and heard in response that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax office employee.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the siege of the Dubrovka Theater, where so many victims perished during the assault intended to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from smelling them.
A precaution entirely useless.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who did not know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same reason.
A policeman came to him and asked, "do you know what the price is?" and the driver replied, "of course, I know," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, or even days for the entire journey.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaeda and all of "the international terrorist network," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the military, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide rebels with false documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers who fight the rebels have, on their side, stocks of ammunition, from which weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this scourge.
Punish corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called "ordinary people" view this phenomenon with leniency.
They say of their mayor, "Of course he steals, but look at all he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people do not like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on board the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption of Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption could well leave the state without citizens, but if the spread of corruption is not stopped, citizens will soon be left without a state.
